      "content": "That’s a common concern, and it reflects a key cultural nuance: in Vietnamese families, even when using technology, the emphasis is on gentle, indirect coordination rather than direct commands. Instead of sending a formal message like \"You must come,\" try starting with a warm, context-rich post in the Zalo group: \“Chào cả nhà, Mai sắp tròn 25 tuổi rồi—nhớ ngày bé nó hay mặc áo đỏ đi chúc Tết, giờ lớn rồi. Có ai nhớ chuyện gì vui về nó không? Mình nghĩ nên làm một buổi nhỏ để mừng, nhưng chưa biết làm sao cho vừa vui mà không làm nó biết…\” (Hello everyone, Mai is turning 25 soon—remember when she used to wear red to Tet? She’s grown up now. Anyone have a happy memory of her? I think we should do a small celebration, but not sure how to plan it without her finding out…)\n\nThis invites participation emotionally and indirectly, letting others volunteer or suggest ideas naturally. It also shows respect for her privacy and avoids putting anyone on the spot."
